</span>
</p>
<p class='talk-transcript__para'>
<data class='talk-transcript__para__time'>
 9:50
</data>
<span class='talk-transcript__para__text'>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='579000' id='t-579000'>What's interesting is, once you hit print --</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='581000' id='t-581000'>and this is from 1450, by the way --</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='583000' id='t-583000'>all of the artifacts of modern comics start to present themselves:</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='585000' id='t-585000'>rectilinear panel arrangements,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='587000' id='t-587000'>simple line drawings without tone</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='589000' id='t-589000'>and a left-to-right reading sequence.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='593000' id='t-593000'>And within 100 years,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='594000' id='t-594000'>you already start to see word balloons and captions,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='598000' id='t-598000'>and it's really just a hop, skip and a jump from here to here.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='601000' id='t-601000'>So I wrote a book about this in '93,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='603000' id='t-603000'>but as I was finishing the book,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='605000' id='t-605000'>I had to do a little bit of typesetting,</span>
